We recommended and Management agreed to:

a.	Direct the Inventory Committee, the GSO, and the Municipal Accountant to reconcile their respective records to reflect an accurate and reliable PPE account balances;

b.	Require the GSO to reconcile her Property Cards with the PPELCs maintained by the Accounting unit;

c.	Require the Municipal Accountant to conform to the standard format of PPELC as prescribed in Section 13 of the Manual on the New Government Accounting System (NGAS) for Local Government Unit (LGU), Volume 2; and

d.	Direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare the necessary adjustments to record the equipment to its appropriate PPE account and ensure that properties meeting the capitalization threshold of ₱50,000.00 be reported as PPE accounts.

We recommended and Management agreed to:

a.	Direct the Municipal Accountant to reclassify all completed projects in the CIP accounts to the appropriate PPE accounts;

b.	Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain CIPLC for each project or construction activity as prescribed in Section 16 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGU, Volume 2 to accurately track the cost incurred and ensure proper classification of PPE upon completion;

c.	Require the Municipal Engineer to coordinate with the Municipal Accountant after project validation/inspection of PPAs with unknown status to determine if completed or still on-going for proper adjustments to the CIP, PPE and Government Equity accounts; 

d.	Direct the Municipal Engineer to promptly submit the Statement of Work Accomplished and Certificate of Completion to the Municipal Accountant upon project completion to serve as the basis for transferring the completed projects from the CIP to their appropriate PPE accounts; and

e.	Direct the Municipal Engineer to submit to the COA Office the Quarterly Report on Government PPAs with complete information on the status of all implemented projects particularly the 11 projects cited in Table VI.

We recommended and Management agreed to:

a.	Require the Barangay Captain of Barangay Bagacay to obtain a deed of donation, in favor of the Barangay of Bagacay, from the owner of the Lot where the community center was constructed, and then process the titling of the lot thereafter; 

b.	Direct the Barangay Captain of Brgy. Bagacay to utilize the Community Center for public purposes only;

c.	Direct the OIC Municipal Engineer to consider only government-owned property as the location of all proposed projects undertaken by the Municipality prior to planning and implementation; and

d.	Ensure that the government funds or property shall be spent or used solely for public purposes and no public money shall be appropriated, spent, and applied, either directly or indirectly, for any religious purposes;

c. 	Direct the BAC Secretariat to submit contracts and its attached documents to the Office of the Auditor within five (5) working days in adherence to the provisions of COA Circular No. 2009-001 and Section 9.1 of COA Circular No. 2012-001; 

d. 	Direct the Accountant to ensure proper and complete supporting documents are attached to all disbursement vouchers; 

e. 	Direct the Municipal Engineer to ensure filling up of complete data in the POs/contracts together with Notice of Award and Notice to Proceed indicating the date of receipt by supplier/contractor signifying his conformity to the terms and conditions of the POs/contracts; and

We recommended and Management agreed to:

a. Facilitate the processing of the Certificate of Title of the untitled lots in order to establish absolute ownership and protect the legal interest of the LGU thereof pursuant to Section 148 of COA Circular No. 92-386;

b. Direct the Municipal Treasurer to facilitate and supervise the proper payments of expenses for the land titling and to update and reconcile the inventory of property assets with the updated records of the Municipal Accountant.

We recommended and Management agreed to:

a.	Submit written explanations for the above audit observations;

b.	Direct the BAC and BAC Secretariat to ensure that the procurement for rental of any equipment be done through public bidding in compliance with Section 46 of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184;

c.	Direct the BAC and BAC Secretariat to adopt alternative methods of procurement in highly exceptional cases and whenever justified by the conditions as provided in RA No. 9184. Henceforth, the BAC shall indicate in the BAC Resolution the specific reasons or conditions that warrant the use of an alternative method of procurement;

d.	Direct the BAC and BAC Secretariat to meticulously and judiciously plan and execute the procurement process, ensure that the most advantageous price is obtained at all times and that the recommendation to award contract be made to only eligible and qualified bidders;

e.	Direct the BAC and BAC Secretariat to ensure that procurement shall be undertaken in accordance with the approved Annual Procurement Plan (APP);

f.	Require the OIC Municipal Engineer to submit a revised SWA containing complete information on the locations and the actual number of hours spent at each project site for each progress payment. Henceforth, the Office of the Municipal Engineer shall maintain records of the actual number of hours spent and the locations where the Backhoe is utilized as the basis of preparing SWA; and  

g.	Require the Municipal Accountant, BAC Secretariat and OIC Municipal Engineer to submit the required documents enumerated in Annex M. Henceforth strengthen the review mechanism in ensuring the validity and completeness of supporting documents for all types/modes of procurement.

We recommended and Management agreed to:

e.	Direct the Municipal Engineer to provide the Inventory Committee and the Municipal Accountant with a complete description and cost segregation of road components on the LRN of the Municipality;

f.	Require the Municipal Accountant and GSO-Designate/Property Custodian to prepare, maintain and reconcile the Local Road Network Ledger Card and Property Card, respectively; and

We recommended and Management agreed to:

